The birds, which have a distinctive 
rich flavour, are shot on the moors in Yorkshire and Northumberland and 
transported to stores in time for the following morning.

M&S, which hopes to tap into a 
growing desire for naturally reared, traditional food, is offering the 
dish as part of a new range of British game.

Rabbit, wood pigeon, venison, pheasant and partridge will also be available from October, when they are at their seasonal best.

August 12, known as the Glorious Twelfth, signals the start of the grouse shooting season, which continues until December.

Gamekeepers and country estates are hopeful that the warm summer weather will make this year's grouse season one of the best for many years

Regarded as the king of game birds, grouse has a distinctive flavour derived from the heather moorland they live on. It is also lean and virtually fat free meat, which makes it a healthier alternative to other meats

The Moorland Associations estimates the £67million English industry helps employ around 1,500 people

The industry has its critics, including the League Against Cruel Sports, which complains of cruelty to the birds, which might be injured rather than killed outright

